NARRATIVE


VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1):

On 04/28/2023 at approximately 0026 hours, I, TFC Todd 6929, was in the area of Beaglin Park Drive and South Schumaker Drive when I observed a white passenger car stopped at the red light at the intersection. When the light turned green, I passed the vehicle as it was still stopped at the green light. I was performing a turn, when I suddenly heard the vehicle accelerate and the exhaust made a loud noise and the vehicle quickly sped up and passed me at a high rate of speed. The vehicle then made a wide right hand turn onto North Park Drive and travelled over the center double yellow lines. I followed behind the vehicle and was able to observe the vehicle going 18 MPH in posted 30 MPH zone and also go over the center double yellow lines again. I was also able to identify the vehicle to be a white Pontiac Solstice bearing MD registration 43104CK. The vehicle’s left turn signal was activated several hundred feet prior to Stone Gate Drive and at one point it appeared the vehicle was going to pull into a driveway. I activated my emergency equipment and performed a traffic stop on the vehicle on Stone Gate Drive off of North Schumaker Drive.

PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2):

I contacted the driver, later identified as David Spence Jones (08/30/1953 2/M), and could immediately detect the odor of an alcoholic beverage coming from the interior of the vehicle. I could also observe his eyes to be red, bloodshot, and glassy, and his movements were slow and lethargic. His speech was slurred when I would ask him questions and I had to ask him to repeat himself on several occasions. Jones stated that he had a couple vodka drinks that night at the Moose Lodge which I know is a bar in the area. I asked him to step out of the vehicle and as he did he stumbled and had to brace himself against his door to regain his balance. I asked him to perform field sobriety to which he agreed. I asked him questions outside of the vehicle and I could now smell the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage coming from his breath away from his vehicle.

PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3):

I first asked him the standardized medical questions. I asked him if he wore glasses or contacts and he stated no. I asked if he took any medication and he stated he is on several medications for his blood pressure and diabetes. Jones also stated that none were a controlled substance. I asked if he had any injuries and he stated that he had “5 disc” taken out of his back and wires in his left knee. He stated several times that he is a paving contractor and that he works every day. Jones answered all these questions in a slurred and slow speech.

The first test performed was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus Test

HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS: (Clues: 6 of 6)

I performed the next test in front of my vehicle on a flat smooth surface free from any debris or obstructions. I explained the test and asked if he had any questions to which he responded with no. I performed the test and observed the following clues:

1 – Lack of Smooth Pursuit Present in Both Eyes
2 – Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation Present in Eyes
3 – Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 Degrees Present in Both Eyes  

Notes: Jones had to be reminded to keep his head still after initially starting the test. He was swaying side to side, front to back, and in a circular motion throughout the testing and at one point I had to readjust my hand placement to be the proper distance to his eyes due to him leaning forward so much. I could also see clearly see that his eyes were bloodshot and glassy.

The national standardization of the HGN test has determined that if four or more clues were evident, it is likely the subjects BAC is at or above .10. This criterion is reliable 77% of the time.



WALK AND TURN: (Clues: 8 of 8)

The next test performed is the Walk and Turn Test. I placed Jones in the instructional position and at one point it appeared that he was going to fall over. I instructed him to stand normally to listen to the instructions given. After explaining the test, I asked if he had any questions to which he responded with no. I the performed the test and observed the following clues:

Instructional Phase:
1 – Cannot Keep Balance
2 – Starts Too Soon

Walking Phase:
3 – Heel to Toe
4 – Off Line
5 – Raises Arms
6 – Improper Number of Steps – Took what appeared to be 10 steps on the return.
7 – Improper Turn
8 – Stops Walking

Notes: Jones stepped off line, missed heel to toe, and raised his arms on multiple steps during the test. He was shaky and wobbly the entire test. He stopped after the initial set of steps for an extended period of time and asked a question and then shuffled his feet to turn. During several steps, he would begin to bring one foot in front of the other than quickly put it down to keep from falling over.

The national standardization of the walk and turn test has determined that if two or more clues are evident or the subject could not finish the test, it is likely the subjects BAC is at or above .10. This criterion is reliable 68% of the time. This test combined with four or more clues on the HGN test is reliable 80% of the time.


ONE LEG STAND: (Could not complete)
Jones was leaning against my vehicle at this time and I had to ask him four separate times to take a step forward away from my vehicle. He finally took a step forward and I then explained to him the one leg stand test. I answered the questions that he had and he attempted to do the test. He then performed it wrong and was shaky and wobbly. For his safety, I determined that he was not able to perform this test and moved on to the next.


ADDITIONAL TESTS:

In addition to the standardized sobriety tests I also completed several additional divided attention tests. I first asked Jones to say the letters F to T without saying anything before or anything after. He started at F and said the letter correctly until he reached P then stopped. He recited the letter in a slurred speech. I was also able to continue to smell the odor of an alcoholic beverage coming from his person.
I asked him to count backwards from 59 to 36 and he started at 59 and counted slowly and in a slurred speech with several pauses all the way to 20 then stopped and asked if I wanted him to keep going.

I then asked him on a scale of 1 to 10 with 1 being sober and 10 being black out drunk where he falls on that scale. He stated he was a 2 out of 10.

I asked him how many drinks he had again and this time he stated three drinks. I asked him what he had to drink and he said in a slurred speech he was drinking vodka and Tito’s. Tito’s is a name for a Vodka. I asked him if he was drinking doubles and he stated and he seemed confused and said no.
I then offered Jones a preliminary breath test to which he refused.

ARREST:
Based on my observations I placed Jones under arrest for DUI / DWI at approximately 0043 hours. I placed him in my vehicle and retrieved his property from his vehicle before transporting him to the barrack. As I reentered my vehicle the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage had filled my vehicle that had not been present before placing Jones inside. While transporting him to the barrack, Jones was talking the entire time with a slurred speech and every time he would speak the odor of an alcoholic beverage would become stronger.
After arriving at the barrack, I read Jones his Dr-15 Advice of Rights and at approximately 0126 hours he refused to take the test. Jones also refused to call a sober driver to pick him up. Due to this decision, he was transported to the detention center to be seen by a commissioner.

I am a certified police officer in the state of Maryland with over 40 hours of training in DUI detection with live donors at the Maryland State Police Academy. I have also completed an additional 16 hours of Advanced Roadside Impaired Driving Enforcement (ARIDE) training through the Maryland State Police. My training, knowledge, and experience have led to several prior DUI arrests and subsequent convictions.
